      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">; it also displaces hydrogen from </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">acids and forms salts. Compounds of lutetium are white or colourless. Lutetium was discovered in 1907 by two researchers working independently: a French chemist, Georges Urbain, and an Austrian chemist, Carl Auer von Welsbach. It was named after Paris - </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fs="i" fa="1" charset="0">Lutetia</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0"> in Latin.</text>
